\paragraph{Primary Statement.}
A quantum field on a Trawinistic manifold is a section of an appropriate fibre bundle whose dynamics are governed by covariant field equations using the Trawinistic connection.

\paragraph{Primary Derivation.}
Let $E\to M$ be a fibre bundle over the Trawinistic manifold $M$.  
A field configuration is a section:

\begin{equation}
\phi:M\to E .
\end{equation}

The dynamics of the field must respect the geometry of $M$, so ordinary derivatives are replaced by Trawinistic covariant derivatives:

\begin{equation}
\partial_a\phi
\quad\longrightarrow\quad
\nabla^T_a\phi .
\end{equation}

A generic covariant field equation therefore takes the form:

\begin{equation}
\mathcal{F}
\left(
\phi,\nabla^T\phi,g
\right)
=
0 .
\end{equation}

\paragraph{Interpretation.}
Quantum fields on a Trawinistic manifold are geometric objects whose evolution is determined by TZP-compatible covariant differential structure.
